segments.text: Okay, then I've got two questions left.
If you could make, if you had the financial capability to make a huge gift, million dollars plus to A&M today, for what purpose would you want that gift used?
Theater arts.
To do what?
Build a building.
Okay.
For the theater arts program.
People are scared of the arts in A&M.
They really are.
Just because they don't understand them, I think.
People don't understand.
If it's not Opus, then they don't want to see it.
Why?
Because they don't trust it necessarily.
They think it might be bad.
They think it might say something that will disrupt their little utopian society of College Station.
They're very talented people at this school, as far as theater goes, that don't have the opportunity to show it because we never get the money.
I mean, we are underfunded worse than I think any other department on campus is underfunded.
Just because theater depends upon money.
You can't do theater without money.
And it just doesn't work.
And it's horrible.
Just because we lose students every semester.
We lose students to other schools.
UT just did away with their undergraduate theater program.
What are we going to do?
What's A&M going to do?
If they're serious about Vision 2020...
I mean, I could go on for this about 30 minutes, but.
Okay.
All right, the last question then is, what feelings do you carry in your heart about Texas A&M?
Eternal gratitude.
Eternal gratitude.
A&M has shaped me into the person that I am.
If I would have gone to a different school, I would not be like this.
I just would not.
I don't think any one of my friends would be.
I mean, I'm eternally grateful in everything.
It's taught me to give in ways in which I never thought I would be capable of giving.
It's taught me to serve in ways that I never thought I would.
It's given me the best friends of my life.
I think other places will do that, but it just seems different here.
And I can't tell you why.
Like, my brother went to University of Virginia, like I said, and he doesn't have the friendships that I have.
He just doesn't.
Just because at other schools,
It's very, I don't want to say selfish, but it's very, okay, what can this do for me?
At A&M it's not like that.
Of course that's always in somewhere, but it's never the driving force.
It's always what can this do for A&M and what can I get out of it and turn of it.
People give here unlike I've ever seen before.
My parents tell me that all the time.
They're like, Ricky, we don't understand what it is, but people just give at A&M.
They just do.
